TI  - Fault-tolerant multi-level customizable human-machine collaborative intelligent manufacturing practical training platform
ST  - 容错式多层次定制化人机共融的智能制造实践教学平台
PY  - 2025
T2  - Experimental Technology and Management
VL  - 42
IS  - 10
SP  - 192
EP  - 200
DO  - 10.16791/j.cnki.sjg.2025.10.024
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105032773366?origin=resultslist
AD  - Fundamental Industry Training Center, Tsinghua University, Beijing, 100084, China
AB  - [Objective] There is a pressing need to cultivate high-caliber talent in intelligent manufacturing (IM) and to optimize the allocation of financial and technological resources in academic laboratory infrastructure. In response to these needs, this research addresses critical barriers hindering the effective integration of industrial-grade IM systems within university practical education. Specifically, it focuses on persistent challenges such as the “technical black box” that obscures system operations, inherent instability in complex manufacturing environments, and inadequate human-machine interaction (HMI) capabilities. To overcome these limitations, we designed, implemented, and validated a teaching platform named the Fault-Tolerant, Multi-Layered, Customizable Human-Machine Collaborative Intelligent Manufacturing Experimental Teaching Platform. [Methods] The architecture of the platform is based on the strategic integration of several cutting-edge Industry 4.0 technologies. Industrial Internet of Things (IIoT) infrastructure provides the backbone for real-time data acquisition and machine interconnectivity across the platform. Digital twin (DT) technology is extensively employed to create high-fidelity virtual replicas of physical systems, enabling simulation-based learning, predictive maintenance visualization, and process optimization experimentation without disrupting live operations. Crucially, a novel fault-tolerant decoupling mechanism was engineered to isolate subsystem failures, ensuring the continuous availability of unaffected production lines for teaching-a critical feature for maintaining pedagogical flow in lab settings. Furthermore, augmented reality (AR) interfaces and other human-machine collaboration (HMC) technologies were seamlessly woven into the workflow, remarkably enhancing operator situational awareness, facilitating intuitive system monitoring, and enabling guided procedural training. [Results] The platform hosts three distinct, representative industrial production lines: a Reducer Assembly Line (focused on mechanical systems), a Surface Mount Technology (SMT) Electronics Production Line (focused on precision electronics), and a Robotic Flexible Assembly Line (focused on automation and integration). This triad collectively forms a comprehensive manufacturing ecosystem capable of producing mechanical components, electronic circuit boards, and fully integrated mechatronic products. Pedagogically, the platform is structured to support a progressive learning journey. Cognitive-level activities utilize DT visualizations and AR overlays to facilitate fundamental understanding. Practical level exercises involve hands-on operation, programming, and troubleshooting on the physical lines. Innovation-level projects challenge students to design, prototype, and optimize new processes or products by leveraging the full capabilities of the platform. A key architectural innovation is the hierarchical, multiline design. This structure inherently promotes remarkable cost efficiencies in both initial construction (via shared control systems, utilities, and software platform) and ongoing operation and maintenance (via centralized monitoring, reduced spare parts inventory, and streamlined technical support). Furthermore, it enables experimental process re-engineering. Where traditional labs constrain students to sequential workflows along a single, monolithic line, our platform facilitates parallel, integrated workflows across multiple lines. Students can concurrently engage with different stages or technologies (e.g., designing a PCB on the SMT line's DT while physically assembling a reducer and programming a robot cell). This concurrency dramatically increases equipment utilization rates and, crucially, boosts student engagement and participation density by allowing larger cohorts to collaborate actively on interconnected tasks simultaneously. [Conclusions] Implementation results demonstrate substantial impact: The platform annually supports over 2,200 student engagements (person-times), accumulating more than 160,000 instructional contact hours. It serves as the foundation infrastructure for 19 distinct undergraduate and graduate courses spanning mechanical, electronic, and automation engineering disciplines. Faculty have developed 11 novel, integrative experimental projects specifically leveraging the unique multiline capabilities of the platform. The technological innovations embodied in the platform have resulted in six formal intellectual property transfers (patents and software copyrights). Most importantly, students trained using this platform developed quantifiably enhanced innovation capabilities, evidenced by increased success rates in national/international engineering competitions and project-based learning outcomes. The modular and open architecture of the platform readily accommodates integration with advanced Large Language Models (LLMs), including DeepSeek and ChatGLV AI, for applications such as intelligent tutoring, natural language processing documentation, and AI-assisted diagnostics within the teaching context. The proven design principles, pedagogical methodologies, and cost-effective implementation strategy documented herein offer a robust, replicable paradigm for advancing New Engineering Education in the global Intelligent Manufacturing landscape. © 2025 Tsinghua University Press. All rights reserved.
