AD  - Department of Agronomy, SRM College of Agricultural Sciences, SRM Institute of Science and Technology, Chengalpattu, India
AB  - This chapter presents a comprehensive analysis of artificial intelligence (AI)-driven predictive maintenance (PdM) systems and their implementation in water treatment facilities. The study examines the evolution from traditional reactive maintenance to sophisticated predictive approaches, emphasizing the integration of AI, machine learning, and digital twin technologies. Through a systematic review of recent implementations and technological advances, we investigate how these systems optimize operational efficiency and reduce downtime in water treatment operations. The methodology encompasses data collection frameworks, AI model development architectures, and performance evaluation metrics, supported by real-world case studies from multiple facilities. Results demonstrate significant improvements in fault detection accuracy (up to 99.50% with stacked convolutional autoencoder models) and substantial reductions in operational costs (25% in the first year) and high-level alarms (97% reduction). The challenges identified include data integration complexities, initial investment requirements, and workforce training needs. The research highlights the transformative potential of AI-driven PdM while acknowledging implementation barriers and future development opportunities. © 2026 selection and editorial matter, Smriti Agarwal and Manoj Chandra Garg; individual chapters, the contributors. All rights reserved.
