UR  - https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105027204114?origin=resultslist
AD  - I-Form Centre for Advanced Manufacturing, University College Dublin, Dublin, Ireland
AB  - Metal Additive Manufacturing (AM) has been widely adopted for the printing of engineering components, however there are still challenges related to process repeatability and reliability. Process Digital Twins (DTs) and Digital Shadows (DSs) supported by in-process AM monitoring data, offer a promising approach to help address these issues. This paper proposes an incremental approach to adopting DSs through Minimum Viable Digital Shadow (MVDSs), leveraging hardcoded physical models to deliver early value, while generating curated datasets for future machine learning based methods. A minimum viable digital shadow, built on a Service Oriented Architecture, is introduced to support this progression. The MVDS initially applies physical-based anomaly detection to Laser Powder Bed Fusion (LPBF) to construct a graph-based digital thread from process data and imagery. Over time, this structure enables the integration of advanced machine learning models (ML). An illustrative case demonstrates how SMEs can evolve from MVDSs to more capable DSs through this approach. © This is an open access article published by the IET under the Creative Commons Attribution License (http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/3.0/)
