AB  - Molecular manufacturing (MM) is envisaged as the future possibility that materials, devices, and systems might be programmatically fabricated at molecular/atomic resolution. This concept was initially articulated by Richard Feynman in 1959, which was later expanded by Drexler, Merkle, Freitas, and others. Recent advances in atomically precise manufacturing, coupled with quantum nanoscience, produce computer chips, medical nanoparticles, and lithography masks. Quantum information and effects can now be integrated within nanostructured systems. This chapter discusses the current status of MM via a three-tiered developmental model of hardware, software, and applications. Hardware includes atomically precise technologies (microscopy-based fabrication and assembly, and DNA nanotechnology) and quantum technologies (quantum dots, spin, and electron engineering, Floquet time engineering, and topological quantum matter). Software includes virtual prototyping systems (“digital twins”) created with game engines, quantum machine learning, and blockchains as the automated economic layer. For applications, some nascent examples of MM are appearing in health and biology, space, energy, and 3D/4D printing. The contemporary notion of MM may unfold as a global scale enabling endeavor instantiated by the orchestrated manipulation of atomic scale matter via a suite of physical-virtual techniques. This might be extrapolated as a grand leveling technology that enables equitable access to opportunities and abundance for humanity. © 2026 selection and editorial matter, Frank Boehm; individual chapters, the contributors.
