AB  - The integration and incorporation of Artificial Intelligence (AI), Internet of Things (IoT), and Digital Twins (DT) in manufacturing has revolutionized industrial automation, enabling smart factories, predictive maintenance, and real-time monitoring. However, this digital transformation also introduces critical cybersecurity challenges, such as data breaches, adversarial attacks, and vulnerabilities in networked industrial systems. Therefore, ensuring the security and reliability of systems based on data-driven technologies embedded in information technology and operation technology infrastructures is of the utmost importance. To address this gap, this paper focuses on developing a workforce capable of handling cybersecurity challenges by introducing a course on cybersecurity education into the mechanical engineering curriculum. The proposed course aims to equip students with the skills to use AI systems securely, detect cyberattacks, and act promptly to take steps to inhibit further damage. By fostering cybersecurity awareness and technical competence, mechanical engineers have the potential to play a crucial role in ensuring the resilience and safety of next-generation smart factories, thus supporting the continued advancement of secure and efficient industrial automation. The proposed curriculum consists of six modules focusing on the fundamentals and concepts of AI and cybersecurity, emphasizing their applications in mechanical engineering. This comprehensive curriculum ensures that participants gain both theoretical knowledge and practical expertise to securely utilize AI systems, identify cyber-threats, and respond effectively to potential risks. Additionally, to substantiate the benefits of such an interdisciplinary course, we include survey results showcasing its benefits. A group of twenty-five Mechanical Engineering students participated in this survey, which showed a significant improvement in their ability to detect cyberattacks following the completion of the cybersecurity training. Copyright © 2025 by ASME.
