TI  - Designing an Educational Omics Data Lake: A Multimodal Infrastructure for Technology-Enhanced Learning
PY  - 2025
T2  - 2025 7th International Conference on Modern Educational Technology, ICMET 2025
SP  - 284
EP  - 290
DO  - 10.1109/ICMET67594.2025.11452000
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105037714062?origin=resultslist
AD  - Center for General Education, National Central University, Taoyuan City, Taiwan
AD  - International Intercollegiate Ph.D. Program, National Tsing Hua University, Hsinchu City, Taiwan
AB  - The rapid rise of Generative Artificial Intelligence (GenAI) and multimodal sensing technologies has created new opportunities for transforming higher education. Traditional digital learning systems primarily capture limited traces such as test results or platform logs, leaving critical aspects of cognition, emotion, and engagement invisible. To address this limitation, this study introduces the Educational Omics Data Lake, a multimodal infrastructure designed to integrate speech, text, physiological signals, environmental data, and learner interactions into a unified framework. Drawing inspiration from the concept of 'Omics' in the life sciences, the architecture emphasizes comprehensiveness, scalability, and sustainability in capturing complex learning processes. The system was implemented through the Uedu platform, which provides real-time data acquisition, cross-modal synchronization, and long-term storage for educational analytics. At the application layer, the infrastructure supports adaptive feedback, digital twin modeling, and generative AI - assisted tutoring. A case implementation in a Python programming course illustrates its practical value: students described generative AI tools - such as QuizGPT and Uedu MyGPTs - as their most supportive resources, helping them overcome debugging challenges, clarify difficult concepts, and build the confidence needed to transfer knowledge into authentic applications. One notable project involved the design of a cross-platform oscilloscope automation interface, where A I functioned as a 'problem-solving companion' throughout the development process. Beyond individual courses, usage records demonstrate that this framework has been actively employed across a wide spectrum of disciplines, including language and writing, education, economics, history, and engineering. Some classes integrated the tools into daily study practices, while others explored them in more experimental ways, reflecting diverse pedagogical approaches and disciplinary needs. These findings suggest that the Educational Omics Data Lake not only enhances technology-enhanced learning in specific classrooms but also provides robust, multimodal evidence of adoption across multiple dimensions of higher education. By integrating infrastructure-level design with broad, cross-course practice, this work positions Omics-based architectures as a foundation for data-driven, sustainable, and inclusive educational transformation.  © 2025 IEEE.
