AD  - 2H Offshore, Paris, France
AB  - Floating offshore wind turbines are deployed in remote and harsh environments, requiring effective strategies for structural monitoring and maintenance to ensure reliability and reduce operational costs. Digital twin technology offers a virtual representation of physical assets that supports real-time insights and data-driven decision-making. This paper presents the development, calibration, and preliminary validation of a physics-based structural digital twin for the TetraSpar floating wind platform, located offshore Norway. The digital twin is built on Finite Element Analysis (FEA) and informed by measured platform motions and environmental conditions to estimate structural stress at critical locations. While machine learning techniques are foreseen as part of future developments, this work focuses on the foundational modeling approach and its initial validation using real-world data. The results demonstrate the potential of the digital twin framework for enhancing structural health monitoring and guiding operational decision-making in floating offshore wind systems. Copyright © 2025 by ASME.
