AB  - This proposal aims to promote the development of a remote educational environment oriented towards engineering students, in order to support the understanding of industrial automation and vertical integration according to the RAMI 4.0 standard. The initiative focuses on the implementation of concepts such as: Industrial Internet of Things, Cyber-Physical Production Systems, and Digital Twins for the remote operation of physical modules in an Industry 4.0 laboratory. The laboratory enables real industrial processes, allowing manipulation, observation, and remote analysis of physical variables such as temperature, flow, and pressure. Currently, the automation of these modules has been developed through an industrial environment based on programmable logic controllers, establishing the control layer. A MOOC is proposed that integrates the teaching of this control through ΠoT and CPPS, integrating a Digital Twins with its SCADA (Supervision), MES (manufacturing execution) and enterprise management) system, to functionally model RAMI 4.0 layers. This architecture will allow students to interact remotely with the operational and administrative layers of an industrial system, strengthening key competencies in digitization and integration of industrial systems. The proposal is inspired by international educational frameworks developed by UNED (Spain) but adapted to the Colombian academic and industrial infrastructure. Results taken from the Cyber-Twin research seed group in the first phase of implementation will be presented, and the design of the MOOC is projected as a scalable learning platform and open access to the Latin community. It aims to contribute to remote education in engineering for I4.0 with emphasis on Digital Twins and CPPS.  © 2025 IEEE.
