AB  - PBL (Project Based Learning) academic environments involving stakeholders such as professors, students, systems, hardware labs and software and hardware developers, administrators, and other specialists profiles to get connected spaces to learn, are based on diversity of systems, data, and events, like students accessing materials, interacting withs project groups, observing and participanting in a professors instructions, doing tests and so on. These events have to be collected by a special class within the system - the Digital Twin - for processing and support of cybernetic capabilities. This paper positions and models a Digital Twin (DT, gêmeo digital) architecture for PBL environment observability. It maps stakeholders' concerns onto the five RM-ODP architectural views, specifies structural, behavioral, and process models that synchronize physical and virtual representations, and organizes dynamic scenarios that demonstrate how the DT can provide subsidies to stakeholders to evaluate overall learning results and efficiency. © 2026 IEEE.
