TI  - Generative AI Driven College English Multimodal Teaching Based on BERT Optimization: An Empirical Study on Interactive Participation and Learning Outcomes in Digital Twin Classrooms
PY  - 2025
T2  - 2025 International Conference on Artificial Intelligence and Digital Ethics, ICAIDE 2025
SP  - 513
EP  - 516
DO  - 10.1109/ICAIDE65466.2025.11189332
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105021947918?origin=resultslist
AD  - Guangdong University of Science and Technology China, Guangdong, China
AB  - The traditional college English teaching model has the problems of insufficient classroom interaction and limited personalized feedback, which makes it difficult to meet the personalized learning needs of students. To this end, this paper proposes a multimodal teaching framework based on BERToptimized generative AI and digital twin classrooms. By enhancing language comprehension ability through BERT, combining intelligent dialogue systems and digital twin technology, it optimizes classroom interaction and improves personalized learning support. This study adopts an experimental control design and conducts a comparative analysis of 200 college students. The results show that the number of questions in AI-enhanced classrooms increased by 35%, the number of teacher-student dialogues increased by 50%, and the proportion of group discussion time increased by 25%. In terms of learning outcomes, the writing scores of students in the experimental group increased by 1.8 points (out of 10 points), oral fluency increased by 20%, and reading comprehension accuracy increased by 15%, all of which were significantly better than those in the control group. Generative AI combined with multimodal teaching and digital twin technology can effectively improve classroom interactivity and learning outcomes, provide a new direction for the development of intelligent education, and provide theoretical support for the application of AI in language teaching. © 2025 IEEE.
