AB  - The effectiveness of industrial bearing fault diagnosis methods is significantly hindered by the challenge of sample imbalance. While digital twin technology alleviates the scarcity of real fault samples by generating simulated data from physical models, the distribution mismatch between twin data and measured signals leads to a decline in diagnostic accuracy. To address this issue, this study proposes a novel twin-subdomain adaptive diagnostic method for rolling bearings with imbalanced data. The method incorporates a channel attention mechanism during feature extraction to dynamically emphasize fault-sensitive features while suppressing irrelevant interference, thereby substantially enhancing the detection of subtle faults. Additionally, a subdomain adaptive strategy is introduced to reduce the feature distribution gap between simulated and real-world data, enabling precise alignment across domains. Finally, the comparative experimental results demonstrate that even under extreme conditions with a sample imbalance ratio as high as 47:1, the proposed method still achieves an average diagnostic accuracy of 75.60%, exhibiting stable and consistent performance improvements over representative methods. These results verify the effectiveness of the proposed approach in aligning the distribution discrepancies between the twin domain and the real domain, as well as in enhancing the generalization capability of imbalanced fault diagnosis. © 2026 IOP Publishing Ltd. All rights, including for text and data mining, AI training, and similar technologies, are reserved.
