TI  - Digital Twin of a 3-DOF Cartesian Sorting Robot: A Mechatronics Education Case Study
PY  - 2025
T2  - International Conference on Computer and Applications, ICCA 2025 - Proceedings
DO  - 10.1109/ICCA66035.2025.11430816
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105036951174?origin=resultslist
AD  - German Jordanian University, Mechatronics Engineering Department, Amman, Jordan
AB  - This paper presents the design and simulation of a 3-DOF Cartesian robot for color-based sorting as a case study in digital twin applications for mechatronics education. Using MATLAB/Simulink's Simscape Multibody toolbox, the robot integrates virtual sensor inputs with embedded control logic. The system features three linear prismatic joints built from imported CAD components enabling Cartesian motion along X, Y, and Z axes. A spatial contact force-modeled gripper simulates object grasping from a conveyor. The hardware components include an Arduino Uno, a GY-31 TCS3200 color sensor, and a mechanical limit switch for object detection and sorting. Control logic is implemented in Simulink and interfaced with the Simscape model; sensor signals drive a state machine to pick and place objects into color-coded bins. Emphasis is on affordability and accessibility: the design uses low-cost, widely available components with open-source tools in a digital prototyping workflow. Simulation results demonstrate coordinated joint trajectories for sorting different colored objects and reliable operation. This digital twin approach showcases how accessible technology and simulation can deliver cost-effective automation, making it suitable for small enterprises and as a teaching platform in educational labs. © 2025 IEEE.
