TI  - Incorporating Digital Twin Technology in Healthcare: Prospects and Constraints
PY  - 2025
T2  - Metaverse Technologies, Security and Applications for Healthcare
SP  - 379
EP  - 392
DO  - 10.1002/9781394305292.ch17
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105013373501?origin=resultslist
AD  - Adani University, Gujarat, Khodiyar, India
AB  - Utilizing the digital twin technology, it is possible to bring new real-time data, advanced analytics, and simulations to change healthcare systems. Metaverse technology makes it possible to explore virtual three-dimensional structures, conduct small-group activities and collaborations, learn through individual self-directed instruction, and teach teamwork skills. Its rapid implementation in the healthcare sector is poised to fast-track digitization breaking through surgery and medical education. The metaverse can offer so many benefits for patient diagnosis and care. It results in better quality patient care, predictive analytics, more efficient clinical operations, and invaluable training and simulation tools. The healthcare industry is using digital patient twins (a virtual copy of a physical system) to continuously analyze, model, and monitor the data in real time. Sixty-six percent of healthcare executives also expect investment in digital twins to increase more than twofold over the next 3 years, according to Accenture. An important aspect is that digital twins can continuously learn and evolve through new data, which, in turn, enables part of their reasoning and rebuilding models for better decision-making. For these characteristics, they are recognized as important healthcare instruments for proactive management and personalized care, with direct impacts on patient assistance and promoting early identification of disease leading to prevention. Capable of ingesting and analyzing large volumes of patient data from multiple sources, digital twins can deliver personalized treatment plans using up-to-the-minute biometric characteristics gleaned from a patient's personal health history. Machine learning algorithms lead to the early identification of health risks and actions are taken beforehand, which gives way to predictive analytics and preventive interventions as well. Additionally, they are a critical piece of the puzzle to enhancing clinical operations and consequently bettering patient care by meticulously analyzing workflows and resource distribution. Digital twin technology relies on AI-ready models and Internet of Things sensor data streaming in from a growing number of sources. So in a way, this method assists the digital twin of the patient by learning insights from historical data to select proper drug treatment or forecast the impact that surgery conducted under certain conditions will have over time as well as managing chronic disease effectively. The primary objective of this article is to explore the many use cases and issues around digital twin technology in current healthcare, augmenting them with additional real-world applications. The final section of the chapter addresses several open research questions that require further investigation. © 2025 Scrivener Publishing LLC. All rights reserved.
