AB  - Aiming at the problems such as low model reusability and few changes in the teaching process existing in traditional modeling methods, this paper proposes a modeling method for constructing a mechanical curriculum teaching platform using digital twin technology. The main work includes three aspects: (1) The procedure initiates with a hierarchical decomposition, breaking down the complex robotic arm into multiple, relatively independent sub-models to enhance modularization; (2) Subsequently, a model design and encapsulation phase is conducted. This segregates the robotic arm's static, dynamic, and control data, encapsulating them into three distinct component types to ensure effective information separation and unity. The internal information and interactions of the sub-models are described using formal semantics like the association matrix and finite state machine, and the compositional relationships are mapped through designed component pointers; (3) Taking the six-degree-of-freedom robotic arm as a case for verification, the results show that, compared with the traditional modeling methods, the construction efficiency has been effectively improved, enhancing the efficiency of teaching and practical application. This research provides a methodological support and technical solution reference for the modeling of the digital twin teaching platform. © 2025 IEEE.
