AB  - The escalating global demand for clean, sustainable energy has catalyzed the exploration of renewable feedstocks, with plant biomass emerging as a pivotal resource in the transition to a low-carbon bioeconomy. This review synthesizes recent advancements in biomass conversion technologies, focusing on the integration of thermochemical and biochemical routes with bioengineering, nanocatalysis, and AI-driven optimization. It categorizes biomass into generational classifications and explores their respective processing pathways, emphasizing innovations in enzymatic hydrolysis, nanocatalyst deployment, CRISPR-based genetic engineering, and microbial consortia. The integration of artificial intelligence (AI), digital twins, and machine learning is discussed for real-time process optimization, feedstock selection, and predictive system modeling. Additionally, the role of emerging technologies such as bio-electrochemical systems, photocatalytic biomass conversion, and energy systems integration with solar, wind, and hydrogen is analyzed. The paper highlights the synergies of co-producing biochar for carbon sequestration, soil enhancement, and energy storage, reinforcing the importance of circular bioeconomy frameworks. Furthermore, it addresses the sustainability implications of biomass valorization across environmental, economic, and social dimensions, underscoring the importance of policy, interdisciplinary collaboration, and infrastructure investment. The study concludes by presenting future perspectives that include advanced feedstock engineering, integration of carbon-negative technologies such as direct air capture, and systemic solutions for climate resilience. Collectively, the findings reinforce that integrated and digitally optimized biomass conversion systems are central to achieving scalable, cost-effective, and climate-aligned energy solutions. © 2025 Elsevier Ltd
