AD  - INTI International University, Nilai, Malaysia
AB  - The swift progression of Industry 5.0 technologies necessitates a significant re-evaluation of technical and vocational education and training (TVET), especially in engineering education. Therefore, it is necessary to investigate the integration of digital twin (DT) and Internet of Things (IoT) into TVET curricula in engineering to cultivate competencies for smart manufacturing, automation, and cyber-physical systems. Traditional engineering training models do not provide students with the skills required for modern industrial ecosystems, such as real-time system monitoring, predictive maintenance, and data-driven decision-making. By incorporating digital twin simulations and IoT-enabled infrastructure, students can gain immersive, hands-on experience in smart factories, energy grids, and intelligent transport systems. The curriculum model developed in this study emphasizes modular competency-based learning, live-data experimentation, and collaborative problem-solving. The model prepares graduates to excel in interconnected and automated environments, thereby enhancing student engagement, adaptability, and innovation. A case study was conducted to analyze the improved technical outcomes and readiness for Industry 5.0 based on the educational transformation. Strategic recommendations were proposed for policymakers, curriculum developers, and industry partners to institutionalize the TVET curriculum. © 2025 IEEE.
