AD  - Thakur College of Engineering & Technology, Department of Electronics & Telecommunication Engineering, Mumbai, India
AB  - The increasing demand for flexible, scalable, and skill-oriented engineering education has accelerated the development of remote laboratories (RALs) that provide internet-based access to real experimental setups. This paper presents a comprehensive review and comparative analysis of remote laboratories in communication engineering and related domains. Early implementations demonstrated feasibility but suffered from limitations in interactivity, scalability, and security. Over the past two decades, landmark initiatives such as VISIR, MIT iLabs, LabShare, and India's Virtual Labs have expanded the scope of RALs across electronics, control, signal processing, photonics, and embedded systems. Despite significant progress, persistent challenges remain, including inadequate real-time feedback, limited multi-user collaboration, insufficient data acquisition (DAQ) integration, and security vulnerabilities. Recent advancements such as cloud computing, Internet of Things (IoT)-enabled smart laboratories, and artificial intelligence (AI)-driven support systems show promise in addressing these issues. This study identifies key research gaps and proposes design directions for next-generation intelligent remote laboratories that are secure, scalable, pedagogically integrated, and sustainable. Emphasis is placed on incorporating cloud-native architectures, multi-user concurrency, and immersive technologies (AR/VR, digital twins) to enhance authenticity and accessibility. The findings highlight that with appropriate design and institutional collaboration, remote laboratories can democratize access to 'anytime, anywhere' experimentation, bridging the experiential gap in modern engineering education. © 2025 IEEE.
