AD  - ASton Webb Suldint Hub, University of Birmingham, Birmingham, United Kingdom
AB  - AI has demonstrated unprecedented potential for advancement in mechanical engineering design optimization, particularly in key areas such as generative design, additive manufacturing, simulation acceleration, digital twins, and automated design. Algorithms automatically generate and optimize diverse design patterns, transcending the limitations of traditional topology optimization. Structural design has achieved a leap beyond human intuition. For additive manufacturing, AI leverages real-time data to intelligently optimize process parameters and defect detection, significantly enhancing production efficiency and quality. Digital twins facilitate instant communication between virtual models and actual systems, facilitating the implementation of intelligent manufacturing and predictive maintenance. While AI technology holds great potential, practical applications still face challenges such as insufficient data, model interpretability, high computational costs, a shortage of interdisciplinary talent, and ethical considerations. This article explores these challenges and proposes strategies such as data sharing, explainable AI, human-machine integration, green AI, educational reform, and ethical management. With the advancement of AI technology, mechanical design will gradually transition to a data- and model-driven phase, facilitating the growth of intelligent, flexible, and sustainable manufacturing systems and injecting new impetus into the industrial revolution.  © 2025 Copyright held by the owner/author(s).
