AD  - School of Modeling, Simulation, and Training, University of Central Florida, Orlando, United States
AD  - Princeton University, Department of Civil and Environmental Engineering, Princeton, United States
AB  - Digital Twins (DT) are emerging technologies that are increasingly deployed across infrastructure sectors. However, many real-world DT initiatives fail due to an overemphasis on technology while neglecting organizational readiness, stakeholder engagement, and strategic coherence. These gaps signal the urgent need for educational programs that prepare professionals not only in technical proficiency but also in the systems-level thinking required to lead strategic digital transformation efforts. This paper presents a novel educational approach developed as part of the Digital Twin Graduate Certificate Program at the School of Modeling Simulation and Training at the University of Central Florida. The course, titled 'Introduction to Digital Transformation and Digital Twins', was designed to address the gap between theory and practice in digital twin education by integrating systems thinking, business analysis, architectural planning, and experiential learning, with support from Project-Based Learning (PBL), the flipped classroom model and collaborative learning strategies. It aims to contribute to the evolving discourse on how to educate a workforce capable of navigating the socio-technical complexities of digital twin adoption. The students and industry sponsors valued the PBL method and agreed that systems thinking improved their understanding of the problem.  © 2025 IEEE.
