TI  - Fostering Industry 5.0 through Engineering Innovation: A Framework for Enhancing Creativity, Problem-Solving, and Early-Stage Technical Competency in Future Engineers
PY  - 2025
T2  - Proceedings of the 2025 IEEE International Conference on Computation, Big-Data and Engineering, ICCBE 2025
SP  - 543
EP  - 547
DO  - 10.1109/ICCBE65177.2025.11255769
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105031169549?origin=resultslist
AD  - INTI International University, Nilai, Malaysia
AB  - The global engineering landscape transitions toward Industry 5.0, characterized by human-centric automation, hyper-customization, and sustainable co-creation. Therefore, it is needed to reconfigure educational paradigms to educate engineers to be equipped with advanced creativity, transdisciplinary problem-solving, and foundational technical acumen. In this study, a framework was developed, leveraging design-driven engineering innovation platforms, such as structured design fairs, to embed Industry 5.0 principles into undergraduate and early-career engineering curricula. Anchored in cyber-physical frameworks integration, digital twin modeling, and human-machine collaborative intelligence, the framework operationalizes experiential learning cycles to promote ideation, rapid prototyping, and frameworkic validation under real-world constraints. The framework is grounded in established engineering epistemologies, incorporating Bloom's revised taxonomy for cognitive development, TRIZ-based methodologies for creative problem-solving, and ABET-aligned frameworks for assessing technical competencies. Empirical validation of the framework was conducted through multi-site intervention studies involving 320 engineering students. Metrics were used to assess computational thinking, embedded frameworks design, sustainability heuristics, and collaborative intelligence in pre- and post-intervention. The results indicated significant improvements in students' abilities to decompose complex problems, demonstrate proficiency in digital fabrication, and apply frameworks engineering principles effectively. The results also presented the potential of innovation-driven educational interventions for advancing Industry 5.0 readiness. Such interventions help to solve the cognitive and technical divide between academic instruction and industrial application. The developed framework integrates ethical, innovative, and human-centric competencies into the curricula, enhancing educational outcomes to meet industrial demands. © 2025 IEEE.
