AD  - University of North Texas, Dept. of Informtation Science, Denton, TX, United States
AB  - This work-in-progress innovation-practice paper presents a targeted approach to educating K-12 students about cyber risks associated with intelligent school transportation systems (ISTS) in the age of emerging technologies such as IoT, AI/ML, Robotics, and Digital Twins. As these technologies optimize school transit operations, they also introduce critical vulnerabilities that must be addressed early. This paper explores cyber threat scenarios specific to ISTS-such as data breaches, system manipulation, and information leakage-within the broader school ecosystem. It introduces the concepts of cyber assets, their hierarchical value, and Cyber Value at Risk (CVaR), and demonstrates how basic arithmetic and modeling techniques can be used to quantify these risks. Using concept maps and Fuzzy Cognitive Maps, the interrelations among security controls, breaches, and potential value loss are visualized. The Zero Trust security model is highlighted as a foundational strategy for minimizing cyber threats in school transportation environments. By integrating these concepts into K-12 ducation, the paper aims to build cybersecurity awareness and critical thinking, equipping students to understand and mitigate risks in increasingly intelligent and interconnected school systems.  © 2025 IEEE.
