AD  - Tallinn University of Technology, Department of Software Science, Tallinn, Estonia
AB  - Computer technologies are now widely accessible. Individuals encounter information technologies (IT) from a young age. Consequently, the importance of computer science and its impactful teaching is increasing. At Tallinn University of Technology (Tal Tech11https://taltech.ee/), the Study Center for IT Foundations emphasizes imparting IT fundamentals to first-year non-IT students, both local and from abroad. A key aspect of the course is the initial assessment, which tests students' prior knowledge in the IT field. The preliminary quizzes provided to students include both practical and theoretical questions based on the course curriculum. The course instructors use these results to assess each student's knowledge level and to define for them an individual learning path. However, the information technologies (IT) industry is rapidly changing nowadays. New technologies such as artificial intelligence, blockchain, internet of things (loT), extended reality, digital twins, etc. provide new services for our daily life every year. In such a continuously changing context, the IT Foundations course does not cover all cutting-edge technologies, focusing on the previously defined course curriculum. Also, educators of the course have limited resources to continuously monitor cutting-edge technologies and add them to the course program. In this paper, we provide the integration of AI and blockchain technologies into the educational process for the IT Foundations course. AI enables continuous alignment of the course program with the evolving IT landscape with technologies arriving in the IT industry, while blockchain, in combination with gamification, aims to increase the motivation of the non-IT students during the course. The approach is aligned with Education 5.0 principles and enables agile course adjustments while enhancing student engagement. © 2025 IEEE.
