AD  - Nigeria
AD  - International Clean Water Institute, United States
AB  - The contamination of water and water bodies is now considered a growing challenge globally, affecting both developed and developing countries. To this effect, researchers and scientific innovators are pushing their limits to ensure that more technologies for developing efficient and adaptive materials in water treatment are actualized. Nanotechnology, particularly the use of nano-sponges, functional membranes, and advanced nanocomposites, is shown to be very promising due to their properties, surface areas, and ability to perform several functions that might seem complicated for conventional materials. One challenge this faces is that the traditional experimental approach to material discovery and synthesis typically requires a significant amount of time and involves multiple trial- and- error processes. Artificial Intelligence (AI), specifically machine learning (ML), is an emerging powerful tool that can accelerate nanomaterial discovery, synthesis, and optimization, specifically for water purification. AI algorithms can be used to predict the relationship between the parameters for synthesis, the performance of the material and in turn help to optimize pore structures, adsorption efficiency, and membrane selectivity etc. in this chapter we explore a method that proposes to integrate AI into the design, synthesis, and deployment of nano- sponges, smart membranes, and hybrid nanomaterials for water treatment, highlighting case studies, simulation techniques, and predictive models. Eclectic styles, converging AI with nanotechnology, can facilitate the emergence of autonomous labs that optimize materials in real-time. It can also lead to innovative manufacturing systems based on digital twins. No part of this publication may be reproduced, stored or distributed in any form or by any means, electronic or mechanical, including photocopying, without written permission from the publisher. Use of this publication to train generative artificial intelligence (AI) technologies is expressly prohibited. The publisher reserves all rights to license its use for generative AI training and machine learning model development. © 2026 by IGI Global Scientific Publishing. All rights reserved.
