SP  - 428
EP  - 433
DO  - 10.1109/KST67832.2026.11432280
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105036802626?origin=resultslist
AD  - School of Civil Engineering, University College Dublin, Belfield, Ireland
AB  - Digital Twin is a relatively new technology in education and there is a limited understanding of how it can effectively be used in teaching engineering. Data-driven modelling is now central to civil and infrastructure engineering, yet most early-stage programming modules still stop at generic exercises. Focusing on pedagogical design rationale and theoretical validation, this paper presents a methodological framework for integrating a Digital TwinMachine Learning (DT-ML) block into a second-year module, i.e., Computer Applications in Civil Engineering at University College Dublin. The redesign has two main contributions, i.e., a three-layer DT-ML pedagogical architecture is proposed, and design principles are derived. These principles connect constructive alignment and experiential, inquiry-based learning to the teaching of DT and ML content. In other words, the redesign aims to strengthen the relevance, coherence and pedagogical depth of the mentioned module as well as examining how DT concepts and introductory ML can be meaningfully incorporated into the module for civil engineering students.  © 2026 IEEE.
