PY  - 2025
T2  - 2025 10th South-East Europe Design Automation, Computer Engineering, Computer Networks and Social Media Conference, SEEDA-CECNSM 2025
DO  - 10.1109/SEEDA-CECNSM68644.2025.11330131
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105034927467?origin=resultslist
AD  - Department of Informatics and Telecommunications, University of Ioannina, Arta, Greece
AB  - Digital Twins are an innovative approach to medical education, allowing realistic simulation of clinical procedures. Their combination with feedback technologies, such as Artificial Intelligence (AI), significantly enhances training in complex and specialized scenarios, such as those related to neurodegenerative diseases. In this paper, we present an integrated virtual avatar system with embedded AI, designed based on data from real patients in everyday environments. This educational environment offers an immersive and interactive learning experience, targeting both healthcare professionals, caregivers and ordinary users, through questions and scenarios that simulate reality. The methodology is based on machine learning models and real-time behavioral simulations, aiming to reproduce symptoms of conditions such as Parkinson's and Alzheimer's disease. The system allows researchers to practice diagnostic and treatment strategies in a controlled environment, while providing caregivers with practical guidelines for daily patient care. In addition, integration into virtual reality (VR) environments is supported. A user study was conducted to evaluate the effectiveness of the system, focusing on user engagement, educational value and clinical applicability. Results demonstrate significant improvement in knowledge acquisition and retention, as well as in the development of diagnostic skills. © 2025 IEEE.
