AD  - Sri Sai College of Engineering and Technology, Pathankot, Punjab, Badhani, 145002, India
AD  - Anurag University, Hyderabad, 500088, India
AB  - Most of AR applications created without following pedagogical design principles lack pedagogical value, resulting in low or no learning gains and difficult integration with existing curriculum and learning goals. The existing AR tools has pedagogical issues like. There is need to bridge the gap between technological features and pedagogical design to make AR tools effective and valuable. This research aims to systematically identify the pedagogical challenges in current AR-based educational applications, derive a validated set of pedagogical principles, and evaluate the impact of applying these principles in the design of ARLEs. By doing so, this study contributes a comprehensive framework that can guide educators, instructional designers, and developers in creating more meaningful, inclusive, and impactful AR-based learning environments. For this purpose a three-phase methodology was adopted in study: 1) pedagogical issues were identified using a systematic literature review (PRISMA framework) and teacher surveys; 2) 21 pedagogical principles were derived and validated by Experts panel using the Delphi method, prioritized using Best Worst Scaling Survey(BWS) method and classified using exploratory factor analysis into five categories: Instructional Design, Technology Integration, Assessment, Collaboration, and Inclusion; and ethics 3) the principles were implemented in the design and development of ARLE and evaluated using an experimental pre-test/post-test design with control and experimental groups. The study results indicated that ARLEs designed on the basis of these principles significantly improved learner engagement, learning gains, and long-term retention of knowledge. The study proposes a validated pedagogical framework to guide the design and integration of Augmented Reality (AR) as an educational technology owing to its positive impact on achievement of learning outcomes. In conclusion, this study shows that augmented reality and a well-designed educational framework can be a valuable tool to improve learning. © 2017 IEEE.
