AB  - Digital transformation has revolutionized university innovation and entrepreneurship education, yet challenges persist in technology integration, resource allocation, and evaluation systems. This study develops an AI-driven optimization framework integrating quadruple helix stakeholders (government-enterprise-university-research): 1gA digital twin ecosystem model identifies curriculum quality (feature weight W2=0.32) as the core coupling factor using random forest algorithm. 2gGenetic algorithm optimizes curriculum resources with AHP-determined weights (α =0.6 demand, β =0.4 cost), reducing matching errors from 32% to 12% after 50 iterations. 3gBlockchain smart contracts with time decay (k=0.1, R2=0.82) enhance university-enterprise collaboration transparency. 4gMachine learning evaluation system achieves 89% accuracy in predicting innovation capabilities via SEM (χ2/df=1.576, RMSEA=0.024) and BP neural network (RMSE=0.32). This research provides a quantitative paradigm for innovation education reform, with regional limitations requiring nationwide validation. © 2026 Copyright held by the owner/author(s).
