AD  - Department of Computer Engineering, Vishwakarma Institute of Technology, Maharashtra, Pune, India
AD  - Department of Mechanical Engineering, Cummins College of Engineering for Women, Maharashtra, Pune, India
AB  - Industry 5.0 presents the advancement of technologies by keeping humans at the center. Personalization, rapid development, security, and sustainability are the core values of Industry 5.0. Several challenges and opportunities are present in the transition of the traditional manufacturing model to Industry 5.0. Rapid advancement of technology, varied demand of customers, and global competition pose major challenges. Industry 5.0 offers opportunities like mass customization, shorter lead time, improved productivity, and a reduction in cost. Human creativity and advanced tools empower innovation. The framework for the implementation of Industry 5.0 consists of various key elements such as artificial intelligence, machine learning, and cloud computing. Use of Internet of Things, digital twin, wireless automation, and robotics facilitates the efficient workflow in the production process. Additionally, additive manufacturing enables mass customization while human-robot collaboration boosts productivity. Addressing data security, privacy, and ethical concerns through strong cybersecurity and regulatory compliance is a critical consideration for Industry 5.0 implementation. Workforce upskilling and reskilling are critical, necessitating extensive training programs and assistance for career changes. © 2026 Elsevier Inc. All rights reserved.
