AD  - Patanjali India Limited, Uttarakhand, India
AB  - This chapter seeks to comprehend the transformative shifts in meaning and the intrinsic digital metamorphoses inside education, as well as the potential for the formation of a new educational network reality founded upon these changes. The discussion centers not on digital innovations and transformations in education per se, but on the necessity to comprehend the potential implications and outcomes of the alterations in social networks instigated by the forthcoming phase of the digital revolution in education. Digital twins (DTs) may be used across several educational environments, from primary and secondary schools to higher education institutions. The students can reproduce complex experiments in a laboratory in a school environment for security and access to resources through virtual representations developed using DT technology. With DT technology, instructors can create virtual field trips where students can see the world without leaving the school environment. With virtual replicas, students can access instructors and even subject matter professionals through virtual representations. It can be instrumental in distance learning when students cannot access a schoolroom or face-to-face instructors. This research examines the high use of DT technology in the educational system, including its technical, social, and ethical limitations. © 2026 Elsevier Inc. All rights reserved.
