AB  - The use of Virtual Reality (VR), Augmented Reality (AR), and Mixed Reality (MR) is characterised by a complex interaction between opportunities and challenges. Some of the challenges include high cost of implementation, problems with compatibility of devices limited availability of content, and lack of framework. The issues associated with users are privacy invasion, and low levels of digital literacy, which cause limited adoption. Lack of awareness or adequate professional knowledge adds to organizational resistance especially amongst small and medium enterprises. The future for immersive technologies looks bright due to the constant development of 5G connectivity, edge computing, and affordable hardware. They allow for integrated, quality experiences to be made more widely available. Virtual and augmented reality solutions have even more significant opportunities for application in the healthcare sector, education, manufacturing, tele surgeries, Smart classes, and digital twins. To increase inclusiveness, the developed applications must address regional and sector requirements. Efforts are needed for development collaborations among policymakers at the government level, technology developers, and the industry leaders to address existing barriers. This chapter explores the opportunities and obstacles of integrating ITs while providing a conceptual roadmap for managing their advantages for various applications to promote their proper and ethical use. © 2026 Nova Science Publishers, Inc.
