AB  - The growing complexity of urban mobility systems and the increasing demand for sustainable transport solutions necessitate the integration of modern technologies into both transport planning and academic training. While digital tools alone cannot replace tested and proven practical approaches, their role as a support mechanism in optimizing mobility and educating future professionals is becoming increasingly significant. This paper explores the use of specialized simulation software and digital models in the context of higher education, with a focus on traffic engineering. Digital transformation in education provides opportunities for students to engage in realistic scenario analysis, traffic simulations, and system optimization without the need for interaction with real infrastructure. The implementation of such virtual environments allows for dynamic experimentation and promotes deeper understanding of complex traffic systems. By utilizing digital twins and simulation platforms such as PTV VISSIM and Data From Sky, students can gain insight into realtime data analysis, infrastructure design, and decision-making processes based on measurable parameters. The study emphasizes that while digitalization enhances learning, sustainable urban mobility ultimately depends on the application of effective strategies tested in real-world conditions.  © 2025 IEEE.
