TI  - Technological Applications of the Metaverse in Higher Education: A Systematic Review of Digital Sustainability Trends.
PY  - 2025
T2  - 2025 International Conference on Green Energy, Computing and Sustainable Technology, GECOST 2025
DO  - 10.1109/GECOST66002.2025.11324547
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105033043677?origin=resultslist
AD  - Department of Computing, Universiti Teknologi Petronas Perak, Malaysia
AB  - Since 2018, metaverse platforms have been utilized as immersive environments in higher education, offering potential for digital sustainability by reducing reliance on physical infrastructure and the need to travel for educational activities. This systematic review examines peer-reviewed studies published between 2018 and 2025 following PRISMA guidelines, inclusion criteria targeted implementations of metaverse technologies, with assessments of sustainability impacts such as resource efficiency and travel reduction. From 974 records, 37 studies were selected for full analysis. The reviewed works cover VR/AR/XR, digital twins, and blockchain-enabled virtual campuses. Findings show that immersive learning can eliminate paper-based activities and minimize campus commuting, thereby supporting more sustainable educational practices. Technical challenges include the high energy demands of hardware and bandwidth limitations. A major gap is the absence of standardized sustainability metrics and comparative energy assessments. Contributions of this review include a taxonomy of metaverse technologies in higher education and a proposed evaluation framework linking metaverse adoption to Sustainable Development Goals 4 and 13. This work offers insights for educators and policymakers aiming to leverage the metaverse for sustainable higher education. ©2025 IEEE.
