AB  - Over the course of human life, we have made consistent efforts to improve our lives using technology. Innovation has led to technologies becoming more affordable over time, making them accessible to more people, resulting in an increased demand and consumption of products, with the increasing human population. This in turn has snowballed to an unsustainable consumption of resources, triggering research and conversation around sustainability. Sustainability primarily focuses on three areas: Reduction, Reuse and Recycle of resources. A lot of resources, ranging from classrooms to furniture and lab equipment, are required in schools to provide quality education. Virtual Reality (VR) has been used to create digital models of processes, systems and physical products (digital twins). A convergence between VR and Education would mean setting up digital twins that elegantly (effectively, efficiently and robustly) simulate different activities occurring in a learning environment. Using digital resources in VR is hypothesized to significantly reduce physical resources consumed at schools. The resources in question include but are not limited to lab equipment, classrooms, labs, furniture, stationery and energy. The authors hypothesize that the elegant replication in virtual environments will result in a reduced consumption of physical resources providing education. For instance, re-usability of VR equipment in different courses allows the use of the same equipment to perform a variety of tasks. The authors seek to conceptualize a value model that will mathematically scrutinize the viability of the hypothesized outcome. © American Society for Engineering Management, 2025.
