AD  - University of Southern California, CA, United States
AB  - Artificial intelligence (AI) and machine learning (ML) are increasingly transforming how complex electromechanical products are diagnosed, serviced, and maintained. However, their integration within the New Product Introduction (NPI) phase remains fragmented across design, manufacturing, and service domains. This survey provides a comprehensive overview of AI-driven diagnostics and predictive maintenance frameworks specifically applied in NPI Service Engineering. The study systematically reviews recent literature and industrial implementations to identify core techniques such as data-driven fault detection, digital twins, and physics-informed models, along with their roles in improving fault triage accuracy, mean time to repair (MTTR), and first-time fix rates (FTF). A structured taxonomy is developed to classify methods based on learning paradigms, data sources, and system hierarchy levels. Comparative analysis reveals that hybrid AI models-combining physical modeling with deep learning-offer the highest potential for early anomaly detection and cross-domain integration. Finally, the paper highlights research gaps in dataset standardization, model interpretability, and real-time deployment within field environments, offering a roadmap for future AI-augmented NPI ecosystems.  © 2025 IEEE.
