AD  - Department of Industrial and Manufacturing Engineering, University of Wisconsin-Milwaukee, Milwaukee, WI, United States
AD  - Industrial Manufacturing and Systems Engineering Department, University of Texas at El Paso, El Paso, TX, United States
AB  - Digital twins are essential for industrial digitization in domains such as aviation and aerospace, smart manufacturing, product development, power systems, urban planning, education, and healthcare sectors. A digital twin (DT) is a virtual representation of a physical object continually updated throughout the physical system's life cycle within a virtual space. It has also taken the attention of researchers in recent years due to real-time data integration, simulation, and the growing complexity of the systems. Because of the complexity of synchronization with physical systems and virtual entities, different processes, implementation methods, and tools have been used to create the DT. This paper focuses on the current research, implementation processes, applications, and challenges of DTs utilizing Model-Based Systems Engineering (MBSE) by exploring literature published between 2016 and 2024. The study examines the critical language, methodologies, and techniques that help integrate DT technology with MBSE. It also talks about system modeling, real-time data synchronization, and different approaches for creating a digital twin in the MBSE environment, especially by using different SysML (Systems Modeling Language) diagrams broadly utilized in research and industrial practice. Finally, the paper also highlights the benefits, challenges, and future directions of developing DTs using the MBSE approach. © 2025 The Authors.
