AB  - The contemporary digital industry is faced with the serious challenge of finding experts who can respond to dynamically evolving technologies, have multidisciplinary skills, and have the ability to adapt in a rapidly changing environment. This is a prerequisite for rethinking traditional learning approaches and implementing innovation, interactivity, and digitalization in modern learning methods. In this context, the paper explores the integration of digital industrial solutions into engineering curricula with the goal to increase student engagement and motivation and to prepare them for Industry 4.0 demands. The digitalization of industrial processes is a key moment for the successful development, optimization, and productivity of modern industry. This paper presents an interdisciplinary educational approach that integrates digital industrial solutions-such as robotic manufacturing, 3D modeling, and virtual process simulation-into the engineering curriculum to enhance student motivation and preparedness for Industry 4.0. The study discusses the implementation of this approach at the University of Ruse 'Angel Kanchev,' highlighting its impact on student engagement, teamwork, and acquisition of Industry 4.0 competencies. A case study based on the Shell Eco-marathon project demonstrates how collaborative learning and digital technologies foster practical skills, innovation, and deeper understanding of real-world industrial processes. The results suggest that the integration of digital industrial tools into education bridges the gap between theory and practice and motivates students to pursue engineering careers.  © 2025 IEEE.
