AB  - The increasing complexity of smart environmental monitoring systems, including air, water, and noise pollution, demands robust methodologies for their design, deployment, and lifecycle management. Digital Twins (DTs), as real-time virtual representations of physical systems, offer a transformative approach by enabling simulation, prediction, and adaptive control. This case study explores the integration of Systems Modeling Languages (SysML) and Unified Modeling Language (UML) with Machine Learning (ML) within the context of Digital Twin architectures for environmental applications. By analyzing state-of-the-art research and engineering frameworks, we identify how SysML and UML facilitate the structural and behavioral modeling of environmental DTs, and how ML components can be embedded into system models to enable predictive and adaptive capabilities. The paper provides a review and a comparative analysis of modeling techniques, tool chains and design patterns of other research papers. It also emphasizes their role in environmental systems monitoring air quality (temperature, PM2.5, PM10, UV), water quality (pH, turbidity, conductivity), and noise levels. Finally, the study highlights existing challenges and proposes research directions for modelbased design, semantic interoperability, and ML integration in future smart city Digital Twins. © 2025 IEEE.
