AB  - Digital sovereignty increasingly becomes a strategic national priority as countries aim to reduce dependence on foreign digital platforms and build stronger digital resilience. Immersive technologies such as virtual reality (VR), augmented reality (AR), and digital twins present significant opportunities for innovation, experiential learning, and the development of future-ready digital talent. This study investigates the determinants of immersive technology adoption by examining digital adoption motivation, perceived value, digital readiness, and technology resistance. Employing Partial Least Squares-Structural Equation Modeling (PLS-SEM), data were collected from 127 respondents with direct experience in immersive learning environments. The findings indicate that digital readiness is the most influential factor driving immersive technology adoption and acts as a key mediator linking motivation, perceived value, and technology resistance. While perceived value contributes positively to strengthening digital readiness, it does not directly lower resistance to the technology. Overall, the results emphasize that enhancing digital readiness is crucial for maximizing the benefits of immersive technologies and positioning them as an important pathway toward achieving digital sovereignty. © 2025 IEEE.
