AB  - In an extraction column, counter-current two-phase flow is generated. The value component is separated from a continuous liquid phase by conveying into a second non-miscible liquid. This work in progress presents a digital revision of this laboratory experiment. It consists of two pedagogically and technically flexible combinable parts. Both parts are inter-institutionally collaborative and are available as a package of executable files.In the first part, an extraction column is operated as a digital twin in virtual reality (VR) usable on home PCs with or without VR goggles. The flow diagram and real laboratory plant setup can be compared, individual plant elements controlled, and alternative control concepts evaluated. Simulated data and real experimental data of the real counterpart of the digital twin supplement the digital twin. The second part of the lab deals with the evaluation of the experiments to find the optimal operating point. Droplet sizes in the captured images are to be classified by applying AI-based image analysis. Students will develop the code using the open-source software Jupyter Notebook. Data-related AI competencies for the working world 4.0 are adressed as a learning outcome. This adresses interdisciplinary integration of teaching content in applied computer science and arbitrary engineering sciences.  © 2022 IEEE.
